<TEXT>
a teenager accused of killing his 
parents and younger brother and sister with an ax was found guilty 
on tuesday his 18th birthday of four counts of firstdegree 
murder 
david brom tried as an adult had pleaded innocent by reason of 
mental illness the olmsted county district court jury deliberated 
about four hours and 45 minutes before returning the guilty 
verdicts 
brom showed no emotion as the verdict was read shortly after 9 
pm 
he was charged with four counts each of first and seconddegree 
murder in the february 1988 slayings the firstdegree murder 
convictions mean that jurors believe the slayings were premeditated 
the trial will move to a second phase thursday to determine 
whether brom was mentally ill at the time and therefore not 
responsible for his actions 
obviously coming in we knew that phase one was not the strong 
part of the case for us 
defense attorney terrence walters had agreed that brom committed 
the murders but argued that they were not premeditated said the 
defense would show that brom is and was mentally ill 
if brom is found to have been sane when the murders occurred he 
faces a life imprisonment sentence with no chance of parole for 17 
years on each of the four counts 
bernard brom 41 suffered 22 ax wounds in the slayings at the 
broms rural rochester home paulette 41 suffered 18 wounds 
13yearold diane had eight wounds and 11yearold ricky had nine 
dr kathryn berg testified tuesday 
olmsted county attorney ray schmitz in his closing argument said 
the number of times each victim was struck by the ax could in 
itself be enough to prove premeditation 
the prosecutor also reminded jurors that brom had many 
conversations with friends in the months before the murders in 
which he discussed killing his family brom did not testify 
walters argued that broms discussions with friends were fantasy 
the plan consisted of a series of disjointed illogical 
fantasylike thoughts flitting in and out of the mind of dave brom 
intermixed with thoughts of suicide walters said 
