a brief look at tuesdays elections around the nation 
us house 
mississippi democratic state sen gene taylor and republican 
tom anderson a longtime aide to us sen trent lott advanced to 
an oct 17 runoff in a race to succeed the late rep larkin smith 
taylor had 42 percent of the vote to 37 percent for anderson and 21 
percent for state attorney general mike moore 
mayors 
atlanta former mayor maynard jackson who served from 1974 to 
1982 reclaimed the mayors office by defeating city councilman 
hosea williams and four longshot candidates by a 5to1 margin 
cleveland city council president george forbes and state sen 
mike white won the top two spots in a nonpartisan mayoral primary 
and advanced to a nov 7 runoff forbes captured 37 percent to 
whites 25 percent the remainder was split by three other 
candidates 
phoenix mayor terry goddard was favored to win a fourth term 
in his race against state republican party chairman burton kruglick 
and real estate broker norris inman voters also were considering a 
proposal to build a downtown baseball stadium 
albuquerque nm mayor ken schultz was trying to become the 
first mayor to be elected to backtoback terms since the city 
switched to a mayorcouncil form of government 15 years ago he had 
seven challengers 
other 
escondido calif a state assembly runoff featured a writein 
campaign by an antiabortion republican dick lyles who opposed 
the prochoice positions of the regular party nominees republican 
tricia hunter and democrat jeannine correia 
