<TEXT>
the extension of steel import restraints once 
a contentious issue in congress is all but assured after an 
overwhelming house vote to extend restrictions until 1992 
mondays 35410 vote approved president bushs compromise to 
extend the restrictions on 29 foreign trading partners until april 
1992 the no votes were all republicans 
sen bob packwood rore has introduced a companion measure in 
the senate where bipartisan approval is expected soon 
bushs plan announced july 25 called for immediate 
negotiations with japan south korea and other leading 
steelexporting nations to extend annual limitations on the volume 
of steel allowed into the united states 
the original pacts which expired saturday were negotiated by 
the reagan administration in 1984 to give domestic steelmakers 
breathing space from subsidized foreign competition 
many steeldistrict lawmakers pushed the administration to 
extend the curbs for another five years but bush opted for a 
smallerscale 2year program in deference to steelusing 
manufacturers the manufacturers argued that the quotas have driven 
up prices and caused supply shortages of some steel products 
the manufacturers had enlisted dozens of lawmakers prepared to 
argue against a fiveyear continuation but the compromise all but 
eliminated the debate house opposition came largely from 
freetraders who felt the steel industry has had enough protection 
its not my first choice said rep bill frenzel rminn 
who had opposed a longer extension nevertheless i have to admit 
its about as good a compromise as could be achieved 
rep joseph gaydos dpa who represents a western pennsylvania 
steel district said the program is not a cureall but has been 
the most effective method of dealing with dumped imports 
this legislation is basically and fundamentally giving the 
steel industry in this country a little more time to become 
competitive and theyre well under way gaydos said 
with the old program due to expire sept 30 the administration 
could not afford to wait until congress acted to begin the 
painstaking process of negotiating new import ceilings 
trade representatives from japan south korea the european 
community mexico venezuela and romania were in town last week for 
meetings on renewing their pacts 
many of the negotiations are already complete said us trade 
representative carla hills even though congress hasnt finished 
work on the bill she said steel imports would continue to be 
monitored by the department of commerce and the us customs 
service 
no details on individual pacts have been announced 
in a prepared statement monday the american iron and steel 
institute applauded us negotiators for their work but stressed 
that the bush program should not preclude american steelmakers from 
