<TEXT>
the standoff over where to bury 
ferdinand marcos is the latest example of body politics a 
filipino game corazon aquinos supporters once played themselves to 
rally a nation and topple a dictator 
rules of the game demand protracted wakes vigils and novenas 
players include grieving relatives who regale reporters 
television audiences and crowds of spectators with tales of 
injustice and appeals to respect filipino tradition 
the object is to play on the filipinos almost mystical respect 
for the dead to promote the cause of the deceased and the fortunes 
of the living 
since marcos died thursday in exile in hawaii manila radio and 
television stations and newspapers have in daily reports showed the 
grieving widow imelda standing before the former presidents open 
coffin 
mrs marcos has vowed to do all she can to return her husbands 
remains to his homeland despite president aquinos refusal to 
allow his burial here 
i also ask for your prayers to give me strength to that i will 
see the victory of my struggle to clear the name of president 
marcos and the whole nation mrs marcos said in a radio 
interview broadcast here today 
the scene in honolulu is an ironic parody of the events of six 
years ago after mrs aquinos husband sen benigno aquino jr 
was murdered moments after returning from the united states to 
challenge marcos 
after the aug 21 1983 slaying the aquino family held a 
nineday wake during which thousands of people filed by to view the 
body still dressed in the bloodsoaked clothes in which aquino 
died 
perhaps two million people turned out for the funeral as 
aquinos body was paraded over a 19mile route aboard a 10wheel 
flatbed truck 
the outrage over the killing galvanized antimarcos sentiment 
and paved the way for the uprising which toppled the longtime 
president and propelled aquinos widow into the presidency on feb 
25 1986 
body politics has been played by lesser figures too 
marcos mother josefa edralinmarcos died on may 4 1988 but 
marcos followers hoped to use her death to dramatize their 
leaders exile and embarass the government into allowing him to 
return the ploy failed 
mrs edralinmarcos remains unburied lying in an open casket in 
batac 250 miles north of manila diehard marcos loyalists carry 
on a vigil which has been largely forgotten 
the military has also discovered the merits of body politics in 
its campaign to discredit the communist new peoples army which is 
waging a 20year insurgency 
under marcos the military tried to hide figures on the number 
of soldiers killed by both communist insurgents and moslem 
guerrillas in the south but no more 
on sept 3 rebels killed 13 soldiers working on a highway 
construction project in quezon province as commanders spoke of 
this outrage television cameras panned the flagdraped corpses 
and grieving widows 
the military also claims the rebels have been carrying out a 
protracted purge of their ranks and have killed scores of party 
members suspected of disloyalty 
with the discovery of every killing field where rebels 
allegedly bury the victims the military encourages television 
cameras to film as bones are unearthed from shallow graves 
at dinnerhour newscasts filipinos watch as elderly peasants 
weep over the bones supposedly of their sons and daughters 
executed by the rebels 
