<TEXT>
a middle school has transformed itself into a 
laboratory on ways to improve race relations where teachers hope to 
erase past tensions and perhaps serve as a model for the rest of 
the nation 
some kids cultural upbringing is different some of it is 
unconscious we need to learn to understand each other better 
says robert pipkin principal of the prospect middle school center 
for multiracial multiethnic and multicultural education 
prospect teachers and their sixth seventh and eighthgrade 
students are learning the fine points of dealing with whites 
blacks asians hispanics and native americans 
the students split almost evenly among whites and blacks will 
learn about the cultures of other races and ethnic groups in hope 
they will find their differences enlightening rather than divisive 
the school in pittsburghs racially balanced mount washington 
section will retain its traditional curriculum but also will 
teach students to recognize racism and its consequences teachers 
also will try to provide lessons free of racial bias 
another part of the program could prove more controversial 
since some studies indicate children of different races and 
cultural backgrounds have different learning styles teachers will 
be taught to expand their repertoire of teaching methods said 
psychologist stanley denton the pittsburgh school districts 
director of multicultural education 
white children tend to be abstract learners in the area of 
mathematics for example they can learn by being exposed to a 
formula denton said 
black children in general learn best when the lesson is 
embedded within a context or accompanied by examples he said 
this is an oversimplification of course he said there 
are always wide variations and exceptions 
attempts to put these theories to work elsewhere have offended 
blacks 
people tend to equate abstract learning with higher thinking 
which isnt the case at all denton said 
administrators hope the program will generate new ideas that can 
be used in other schools in pittsburgh and perhaps across the 
country 
we want a program that will celebrate diversity and encourage 
kids to be proud of their background and knowledgeable about their 
cultural heritage denton said 
the first year of the program will involve mostly training and 
planning next september however the center will begin projects 
designed to enhance students selfesteem teach the histories of 
different minorities and sensitize teachers to their own racial 
attitudes 
about 52 percent of the districts 39500 students are black and 
47 percent are white one percent come from other minority groups 
of prospects 625 students 48 percent are black 
the district invited teachers to apply to work in the new 
program and 90 percent of prospects teachers and staff are new to 
the school this year 35 percent or 21 of the schools 59 
fulltime teachers are black and the rest are white 
the idea for the changes sprang from a study that found black 
male students in pittsburgh got suspended from schools more often 
than others 
we also had a couple of incidents of racism pipkin said 
we had some teachers making blatant remarks about afroamerican 
kids and episodes between back and while students some racial 
name calling 
changes also were suggested by business and community advisers 
concerned about black students complaints of racial harassment at 
colleges and universities including pennsylvania state university 
indiana university of pennsylvania and carnegie mellon university 
