<TEXT>
the us occupational safety and health 
administration reportedly intends to push for regulations to 
protect millions of rescue workers from exposure to aids and other 
bloodborne diseases 
the measures estimated cost is 800 million the highest figure 
in the agencys history the atlanta journalconstitution reported 
today 
the regulations are needed because a cavalier attitude 
toward infections is increasing the danger of sickness and death 
among health workers said dr joseph h coggin jr a consultant 
to osha 
an estimated 53 million nurses police officers ambulance 
drivers embalmers firefighters and prison guards would be covered 
by the regulations 
in spite of a barrage of literature about the modern dangers 
