<TEXT>
alaskas efforts to prevent oil and gas 
exploration in the rich fishing grounds of bristol bay focused on 
congress as the us supreme court declined to hear the states 
latest appeal 
the court monday left intact rulings that allowed the federal 
government to sell 94 million worth of exploratory leases last 
year on 56 million acres of the bay off southwest alaska 
it means as we suspected that the battle has shifted to 
congress which is moving in the direction of protecting bristol 
bay from development said randall weiner executive director of 
the environmental group trustees for alaska 
state attorney general douglas baily said he was not surprised 
by the courts action weve been focusing on congress in part 
because we didnt want to trust all of our eggs in the basket of 
the supreme court 
state officials environmental groups and fishing organizations 
have said the relatively small chance of finding large amounts of 
oil under bristol bay is not worth the risk of an oil spill to fish 
and wildlife 
they also contend that a spill would do more environmental harm 
there than the exxon valdez spill did to prince william sound the 
march 24 tanker disaster the nations worst oil spill forced the 
closure of several fishing areas 
bristol bay supports the worlds largest red salmon fishery 
worth more than 1 billion annually and the largest herring 
fishery in us waters it also is home to a majority of the 
worlds northern fur seals the pacific gray whale population and 
millions of seabirds geese and ducks 
bristol bay is the only place weve opposed oil development 
and for one chief reason the risk to the fishery isnt worth the 
potential oil spill said gov steve cowper the courts action 
is disappointing but shouldnt be a surprise to anyone 
an agreement in a housesenate conference committee last week 
would prohibit any drilling in the bay for a year and require the 
interior department to consider buying back the leases 
under the plan any buyback recommendation would be tied to the 
results of an interior department study of the effects of the exxon 
valdez spill that study also would look at the adequacy of 
spillcontingency plans for bristol bay development only congress 
could authorize the repurchases 
the agreement is contained in the departments fiscal 1990 
spending bill which was expected to return to the house today and 
the senate by wednesday for final approval said jane robbins 
press secretary for sen ted stevens ralaska 
the studies and interiors recommendation are due by march 1991 
meaning no exploration is likely in bristol bay before then 
