<TEXT>
five amateur astronomers are preparing for an 
undreamedof opportunity to go eyeball to eyeball with the universe 
using what will be the worlds most powerful space telescope 
in a gesture of appreciation for scientific contributions by 
hobbyists using backyard telescopes the space telescope science 
institute has offered 20 hours of observing time on the hubble 
space telescope to projects designed by amateurs 
the telescope to be launched on a space shuttle in march is a 
joint project of the national aeronautics and space administration 
and the european space agency the project based at johns hopkins 
university is expected to cost about 750 million and has been in 
planning stages for a decade 
for someone who is not a professional astronomer the odds of 
getting to use the telescope are comparable to george jetsons 
chances of getting a raise from his tightfisted boss at spacely 
sprockets 
i would guess every amateur astronomer would love to use it 
said one of those selected james secosky a science teacher from 
rochester ny i never thought id get to use an instrument like 
this 
but astronomy is one of the few scientific fields in which 
amateurs make significant breakthroughs 
for example edwin hubble the american astronomer for whom the 
telescope is named developed his theory of the expanding universe 
in cooperation with milton humason a former janitor mule driver 
and highschool dropout 
in actuality outer space begins in your back yard all you 
need is a good pair of binoculars to get started said pete 
kandefer an electrical engineer from new hartford conn who also 
was chosen 
others selected include a computer expert and a homemaker 
professionals already have overbooked time on the telescope the 
first major optical telescope that will be permanently stationed in 
low earth orbit said ray villard an institute spokesman 
the 24000pound instrument about the size of a bus has a 
24meter mirror that will gather enough light to enable 
researchers to make images of things that are 25 to 50 times 
fainter than the dimmest object previously seen 
free of the atmospheres distortion of distant light and the 
earths tendency to absorb the extreme ends of the light spectrum 
the telescope will produce pictures 10 times clearer than anything 
available on the ground villard said 
if your eyes were as good as the telescope you would be able 
to see a dime 20 miles away and know it was a dime villard 
said 
secosky 42 is interested in why jupters moon io sometimes 
appears brighter as it emerges from the planets frigid shadow he 
thinks his observations may detect evidence of frost forming on the 
moon 
kandefers regular job is working on flight controls and 
guidance sensors but the 42yearold engineer spends his free time 
trying to learn about steller magnetic fields 10 times stronger 
than the suns 
the only woman in the group ana larson 41 of seattle was 
half a dozen years into an accounting career when she decided to 
take time off to raise her two children and fell in love with 
astronomy through university of washington correspondence courses 
her goal is to find huge planets taking form around stars a 
process scientists suspect is occurring but cannot prove because it 
is so difficult to distinguish any object that close to a stars 
brightness larson hopes to find planets five to 10 times larger 
than jupiter that release enormous amounts of energy detectable to 
a telescope as heat 
ray sterner a 37yearold computer scientist at hopkins will 
test his theory that luminescent arcs discovered in a distant 
galaxy cluster are made of stars most astronomers consider such 
arcs to be optical illusions caused by gravity bending starlight 
john hewitt who works at a science museum in berkeley calif 
hopes to detect a hypothetical mass of primordial material 
surrounding a star where comets could take form 
we arent professional scientists and we would not qualify as 
observers under the regular procedures hewitt said this is an 
incredible opportunity for an amateur astronomer on what is 
esentially the most capable astronomical instrument ever created 
