the barco administration in its war against the drug lords and 
would help allay fears that the court could undermine the antidrug 
crackdown 
tv hoy said however that the court would declare 
unconstitutional an additional decree allowing the colombian army 
to raid drug traffickers property at will 
it said the court will support the governments right to 
confiscate property from drug traffickers but will require that it 
go through judicial channels 
the court will not decide on the legality of property already 
seized leaving that issue for lower courts tv hoy said 
as of a week ago the army had seized 1056 homes ranches 
mansions office buildings and other property allegedly belonging to 
drug traffickers 
the administrations main weapon in the drug war is its power to 
extradite suspected drug figures who have repeatedly shown their 
ability to escape justice in colombia 
the united states has a list of 80 colombians it wants 
extradited to face drug charges but it has disclosed the names of 
only the top 12 
in 1984 the supreme court ruling on a technicality declared 
extraditions to the united states unconstitutional 
the court has not dealt favorably with other important barco 
decrees before barco declared war on the traffickers aug 19 the 
court had knocked down seven decrees he issued in attempts to deal 
with both guerrillas and drug traffickers 
the most important of earlier decrees declared unconstitutional 
was one creating a special tribunal within the supreme court to 
