<TEXT>
the henry j kaiser family foundation 
announced thursday it is spending nearly 700000 on model programs 
to encourage people in 10 states including nebraska farmers 
harlem blacks and tourists in las vegas casinos to eat less fat 
we are taking this campaign to the heartland of america 
alvin tarlov president of the foundation said in announcing the 
twoyear grants under the foundations project lean an acronym for 
lowfat eating for america now 
he said the programs will be monitored for their effectiveness 
by teams from the centers for disease control and stanford 
university and vary widely from state to state 
thus in new york the project lean program will focus on 
reaching blacks and hispanics in four communities washington 
heights harlem east harlem and bedfordstuyvesant he said 
baltimore will be targeting the 60 percent of the citys 
population that is nonwhite by aiming at 24 contiguous 
neighborhoods in west baltimore 
dr j michael mcginnis deputy assistant secretary for health 
said minorities the elderly and lowincome people have higher 
rates of chronic diseases than the general population and they can 
also be the most difficult to reach with the information and 
support that can foster beneficial change in health behaviors 
nebraska will be trying to reduce fat consumption in one of 
the key farm states tarlov said and las vegas will be 
targeting the millions of tourists eating out during their 
vacations and conventions 
gary edwards director of lifestyle assessment for the utah 
department of health said project workers in utah would help 
supermarkets mark shelves to identify lowfat foods he said the 
program also would include grocery tours for students 
robert mancke director of the maryland bureau of health 
education said the bureau had commitments from two supermarkets 
one minorityowned and one with many nonwhite customers to label 
and promote lowfat products in addition a baltimore organization 
called creative community would present skits and other 
performances on the theme of more healthy eating 
the grants are 
to the maricopa county department of health phoenix ariz 
60000 to expand a program of dieticianled tours in supermarkets 
shopping guides and recipes 
to the california public health foundation berkeley calif 
70000 in support of a coalition including the bay area cancer 
coalition the california beef council a supermarket chain and the 
university of california 
to the baltimore health department 70000 to reduce fats in 
the diets of innercity residents in collaboration with the state 
health department and baltimore city alliance for high blood 
pressure 
to the new york city department of health 70000 for a 
program aimed at reducing fat consumption among blacks and 
hispanics using project lean materials and other resources 
to the nebraska department of health 70000 for programs in 
supermarkets work sites and schools and a media campaign 
to the university of nevada cooperative extension las vegas 
70000 for a program targeting the casino and restaurant 
industries in an effort to reduce fat consumption of tourists and 
others eating away from home 
to the rhode island department of health 60000 for a 
supermarket and media campaign 
to the utah department of health 70000 for a program aimed 
at public school curricula school lunch programs and retail 
supermarkets in davis and wasatch counties 
to the virginia department of health for a statewide 
information campaign and targeted efforts in the hampton roanoke 
and thomas jefferson health districts 
to the west virginia department of health for coordination of 
statewide and community campaigns through the media food outlets 
professional health organizations and public events 
