<TEXT>
spurred by concerns about scientific misconduct 
a prestigious medical journal will require study authors to hand 
over their raw data for examination if requested the journal 
editor said tuesday 
the journal also will tighten its requirement on disclosing 
financial interests involved in the research said george lundberg 
of the journal of the american medical association 
the steps are among requirements being imposed to protect the 
credibility of the journal lundberg said the requirements will 
take effect when they are announced in next weeks issue he said 
at a science reporters conference sponsored by the ama 
were calling attention to all these things hoping by 
education or intimidation to keep things straight he said in an 
interview 
to get research published in the journal scientists will have 
to sign a pledge that they will let editors examine their raw data 
if the editors ask for it lundberg said that will help in 
detecting misrepresentation of data or fraud he said 
the journal already asks authors to disclose financial interests 
in their work and weve trusted authors to level with us 
lundberg said the journal will go a step further by requiring a 
signed certification 
financial interests include who paid for the research who 
employs the researchers whether a researcher owns stock in a 
company that would be affected by the study and whether the 
scientist is a paid consultant to such a company 
such information may be published along with the study lundberg 
said 
study authors also will have to certify that they participated 
in the reported work enough to take public responsibility for it 
lundberg said that is aimed at the practice of honorary 
authorship in which a listed author may not have played a 
meaningful role in the study 
in some recent medical fraud cases distinguished scientists who 
were listed as authors had never seen the paper and did not even 
know the reported research was bogus he said but the appearance 
of their names on the papers lent the works credence he said 
authors also will have to vouch for the validity of the study 
and certify that they had reviewed and approved the final 
manuscript 
if an author lies in making the newly required statements the 
journal may publish a notice about it lundberg said 
in a separate presentation at the conference a prominent heart 
disease researcher said federal funding for biomedical research 
should be set as a fixed fraction of the nations spending on 
health care 
without such steps to assure adequate funding in the future the 
field will have trouble attracting young researchers and replacing 
antiquated equipment said antonio gotto of baylor college of 
medicine in houston 
that in turn would endanger its ability to conduct the science 
that leads to new products for health care he said 
in 1985 the nation spent 458 billion or about 108 percent of 
its gross national product on health care costs he said 
federal funding of medical research has declined to about 12 
percent of overall gnp from previous levels of 3 percent he said 
a return to the previous level might be an appropriate target he 
said 
douglas kelly associate vice president for medical research of 
the association of american medical colleges said he believed the 
fixedpercentage idea is not very realistic politically 
it would convert research funding to an entitlement like social 
security and congress would probably be reluctant to do that he 
said in an interview 
