a nationwide credit company agreed tuesday to 
pay 275000 in civil penalties in the largest settlement ever 
obtained by the federal government under the equal credit 
opportunity act 
the federal trade commission had charged the general electric 
capital corp discriminated against applicants to its instant 
credit program on the basis of age sex marital status and 
receipt of income from public assistance 
the record settlement came in a proposed consent decree filed by 
the justice department in us district court in conneticut the 
settlement ended a 4year ftc investigation 
the decree does not constitute an admission by ge capital of 
the alleged violation and was signed by the company to avoid 
protracted and expensive litigation said ge capital spokeswoman 
lisa van orden 
according to the ftc complaint a requirement by ge capital that 
persons applying for instant credit be employed full time 
discriminated against the elderly and divorced women 
the ftc said the policy was discriminatory because it didnt 
take into account elderly and divorced womens incomes from 
alimony child support separate maintenance annuity pension 
parttime employment social security or other government programs 
the alleged violations occurred in 1985 and 1986 at furniture 
department discount appliance doityourself and lawn and 
garden stores nationwide where ge capital offered credit for 
consumer purchases 
