<TEXT>
police misconduct is likely to increase if the 
supreme court creates a new loophole in the rule barring unlawfully 
obtained evidence from criminal trials a chicago lawyer warned 
tuesday 
expansion of the use of unlawfully obtained evidence is a 
major step the court should not take at this time said martin 
carlson arguing in behalf of a young convicted murderer before the 
supreme court it would add significant incentive to police to 
violate protected rights he contended 
but terence madsen an assistant attorney general for illinois 
said the justices would enhance the truthseeking process of 
criminal trials nationwide if allowing such an expansion 
the states arguments are supported in a friendofthecourt 
brief submitted by the bush administration 
at issue in the case to be decided by july is whether 
statements a criminal defendant makes after an unlawful arrest may 
be used by prosecutors to contradict a defense witness trial 
testimony 
the socalled exclusionary rule created by the supreme 
court nearly 75 years ago generally prohibits the use at trial of 
any illegally obtained evidence 
the high court later carved out an exception to the rule by 
allowing prosecutors to use such evidence to contradict a 
defendants own trial testimony but the justices never have said 
such evidence may be used to rebut or discredit other witnesses 
testimony 
the illinois supreme court by a 43 vote allowed such evidence 
to be introduced at the trial of darryl james sentenced to 30 
years in prison for a 1982 murder 
james was 15 when arrested in his mothers beauty parlor for a 
pair of aug 30 1982 shootings he was tried as an adult 
prosecutors said james shot and killed geliria boyd and wounded 
another youth in a latenight confrontation on a south chicago 
street 
several prosecution witnesses identified james as the 
triggerman and testified that on the night of the crime he had 
long reddishbrown hair 
at his trial james had short black hair 
james did not testify but two defense witnesses testified in his 
behalf one said that james had short black hair the night of the 
shootings 
prosecutors then won the judges permission to let a police 
detective testify that james when arrested said he had long 
reddishbrown hair the night of the crime and that he had his hair 
dyed and cut at his mothers shop 
the trial judge previously had disallowed such testimony ruling 
that james arrest was unlawful because police at the time did not 
have a court warrant or probable cause to suspect him of committing 
a crime 
madsen the states lawyer was questioned rigorously by justice 
john paul stevens the courts only illinois native 
if unlawfully obtained evidence can be used by prosecutors any 
time a defendant mounts any kind of defense stevens suggested 
police would have every incentive to bend the rules 
police departments around the country would alter their 
procedures to make sure such evidence is obtained stevens said 
but madsen disagreed saying its not correct to presume that 
the police would not do it right 
the case is james vs illinois 886075 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

