<TEXT>
his clients industries read like an 
environmental hit list nuclear energy chemicals hazardous waste 
disposal and lawn care 
its not surprising that bruce mccarthy has made a big business 
out of crisis public relations 
companies that have turned to him for help include wr grace amp 
co borden incs chemical division and chemlawn corp 
he helped kemper insurance pull out of the highly regulated 
massachusetts auto insurance market without incurring fines and he 
represents new hampshire yankee operator of the troubled 
overbudget seabrook nh nuclear power plant 
mccarthys first job of course is to help such clients avoid 
debacles in the first place 
we tell them you live in a fishbowl today and you have to 
expect everything you do and say is going to land on the front page 
of your newspaper he said youre not going to be able to go 
back to your boardroom and communicate with no one but your 
shareholders those days are gone 
so when oil spills radiation leaks or regulatory agencies 
sting when government inspectors arrive to seize files and 
reporters descend to put tales of corporate wrongdoing on page one 
mccarthy provides damage control 
he prescribes an oldfashioned remedy newly in vogue in 
crisismanagement public relations tell all apologize if 
necessary make amends before the government and the courts make 
them for you 
full disclosure is where its at mccarthy said 
recentlydrench any kind of a crisis and any kind of a difficult 
story in information get it all out very quickly and assume its 
all going to come out in the end 
he argues that stonewalling only encourages reporters to dig for 
themselves with help from the corporations foes if a company 
gets the facts out fast the media will quickly lose interest in 
the story 
mccarthys nemesis is the corporate attorney 
when disaster strikes attorneys frequently counsel executives 
to say as little as possible and especially not to apologize lest 
those statements be used against them in a liability suit 
often times the attorney wins and that leads to negative 
stories that run on for days said mccarthy 54 who cut his 
teeth in public relations as a utility company spokesman during the 
arab oil embargo then eventually the company relents and decides 
to open up but by that time so much damage has been done and they 
are so defensive that it usually works against them 
advice costs 50 to 200 an hour at mccarthys 5yearold bmc 
strategies inc in the boston suburb of lexington 
though he has been successful his staff of 30 is up against 
tough competitors including major law firms with more specializing 
in governmental relations that can mean anything from lobbying 
lawmakers to negotiating with regulatory agencies to running 
interference with the media 
william weld former head of the us justice departments 
criminal division has launched a unit within the boston law firm 
of hale amp dorr representing companies or individuals who find 
themselves the targets of white collar crime investigations 
weld agreed that candor usually pays but he said he would 
advise the company to meet privately with government officials 
first 
the worst thing i think for a company in trouble to do is 
for the ceo to go public and declare we are blameless and then 
be left twisting in the wind as three weeks of negative details 
come out weld said 
but he warned you dont want to take a shot into the unknown 
and make a statement which is essentially a guilty plea toward a 
felony without having some notion of what the government attitude 
is likely to be 
kate mcdonough managing director of the adams amp rinehart public 
relations agency in new york said the way a company responds to a 
crisis can influence prosecutor judge and jury 
did the company try to cover up or did it act responsibly 
those are issues that are legitimately put before the court 
mcdonough said 
whether the public approves of a companys response to a 
disaster can affect the bottom line just as much as a lawsuit she 
added 
because of johnson amp johnsons quick candid and aggressive 
response to the tylenol poisonings a few years ago the market 
share of the painkiller actually increased after the incident she 
said but exxon corp widely faulted for its response to the 
valdez oil spill was threatened with a consumer boycott 
