<TEXT>
brazil the worlds biggest coffee producer 
dashed hopes wednesday of any early agreement to bring the 
depressed world coffee market back under international control 
brazils chief coffee executive jorio dauster said there was 
no chance of having quotas again in the near future because 
members of the international coffee group cant come to terms on 
export limits that ultimately set prices 
dauster heads the brazilian delegation attending talks in london 
at the international coffee organization 
i dont see any real change in the positions that led us into 
the deadlock dauster told reporters at a news conference we 
should not rush into new negotiations unless we see that the 
elements that led us to deadlock have been removed 
the organization monday announced a twoyear extension of the 
international coffee agreement retroactive to sunday but without 
any pricesupport provisions 
the agreement keeps in existence the international coffee 
organization as a forum for discussing matters of mutual concern to 
41 coffee exporting countries and 18 importing countries 
the organization was propping up prices in the glutted world 
market through export quotas aimed at supporting prices of beans at 
120 per pound or more 
the organizations regulatory powers were suspended indefinitely 
on july 4 after the united states pulled out in a price dispute 
with coffeeproducing nations the united states wanted an increase 
in export quotas for higherquality coffees enjoyed by us 
consumers 
since july the price of coffee beans has dropped by more than 
30 percent to a 14year low threatening a huge loss in income for 
producing countries such as uganda the ivory coast colombia and 
most central american nations where coffee is one of the top 
foreign income earners 
the suspension of quotas followed a fight among producers over 
export market shares 
in the previous negotiations brazil resisted moves to cut its 
30 percent share of the export quota to bump up the allocation of 
central american producers of the popular mild arabica variety 
colombia the worlds second biggest producer has led the 
campaign to bring back quotas seeing increased export earnings as 
critical to help it finance the fight against the countrys drug 
cartel 
